V-Ray Python Binding Module

class vray.AColor¶

Bases: vray.Color

V-Ray AColor

An extension of vray.Color that adds an alpha channel as the 4th component. “alpha” means opacity, the opposite of transparency.

AColor() -> new AColor with value (0, 0, 0, 1) AColor(color, alpha) -> new AColor from a Color object with added alpha AColor(red, green, blue, alpha) -> new AColor full constructor

a¶

AColor alpha component

alpha¶

AColor alpha component

class vray.Color¶

Bases: object

V-Ray Color

A 3-component floating point color value. It supports mathematical operations, indexing and equality checking. In most contexts the component values are in the range (0; 1), but in lighting calculations HDR values above 1.0 are possible.

Color() -> new Color with value (0, 0, 0) Color(red, green, blue) -> new Color full constructor

b¶

Color blue component

g¶

Color green component

r¶

Color red component

class vray.List¶

Bases: list

V-Ray List

An extension of a normal Python list that allows setting a fixed type for homogenous V-Ray parameter arrays.

getType()¶

Returns the VRay List type as a string.

setType()¶

Sets the VRay List type according to the given string value. List type must be one of the following string values: ‘IntList’, ‘FloatList’, ‘VectorList’, ‘ColorList’ or just ‘List’.

class vray.Matrix¶

Bases: object

V-Ray Matrix

A 3x3 column-major matrix. Each column is a vray.Vector that can be indexed. The usual mathematical operations are supported as well as equality checks.

Matrix() -> new Matrix initialized to all zeroes Matrix(diagonal) -> new Matrix initialized with ‘diagonal’ along the diagonal Matrix(col0, col1, col2) -> new Matrix initialized with the 3 vray.Vector-s

column0¶

Column0 of the matrix

column1¶

Column1 of the matrix

column2¶

Column2 of the matrix

static makeRotMatrixX()¶

[deprecated] Creates a clockwise rotational matrix around the x axis given an angle in radians.

static makeRotMatrixY()¶

[deprecated] Creates a clockwise rotational matrix around the y axis given an angle in radians.

static makeRotMatrixZ()¶

[deprecated] Creates a clockwise rotational matrix around the z axis given an angle in radians.

static makeRotationMatrixX()¶

Creates a rotational matrix around the x axis given an angle in radians.

static makeRotationMatrixY()¶

Creates a rotational matrix around the y axis given an angle in radians.

static makeRotationMatrixZ()¶

Creates a rotational matrix around the z axis given an angle in radians.

class vray.Plugin¶

Bases: object

V-Ray Plugin

A wrapper for a Plugin instance in the V-Ray core. It exposes the instance’s properties as a dictionary. Deleting (unbinding) this object does not alter the V-Ray scene. You have to ‘del’ the plugin from VRayRenderer.plugins in order to remove it from the scene.

getClass()¶

Returns the class of this plugin as a string.

getMeta()¶

Obtains a runtime meta information dictionary about all properties (if no arguments) or about a particular one (if a name is given as an argument). ‘Runtime’ in this case means that the type of a property value might differ from that in the plugin class meta info.

getName()¶

Returns the name of this plugin instance as a string.

getRenderer()¶

Returns the VRayRenderer instance to which this plugin belongs.

getType()¶

Returns the type of this plugin as a string.

getValueAsString()¶

Returns the value of a property as a string. If the property type is Plugin, the instance name is returned. None is returned upon failure.

isPropertyAnimated()¶

Returns whether the currently contained value in the property is animated. Argument: propertyName, string

replaceWith()¶

Replaces all references to this plugin instance in the scene with another. Argument: replacement, Plugin or string or None - if None, the references are deleted and become empty

setName()¶

Changes the name of this plugin instance. All existing references to it in plugin properties that are plugin references are updated and remain valid.The boolean result indicates success or failure of the operation.

setValue()¶

Sets the value of a property. The boolean result indicates success or failure of the operation.

setValueAsString()¶

Sets the value of a property from a string. If the property type is Plugin, the instance name should be passed. The boolean result indicates success or failure of the operation.

vray.Renderer¶

alias of VRayRenderer

vray.Server¶

alias of VRayServer

class vray.Transform¶

Bases: object

V-Ray Transform

The object is a composite of a vray.Matrix and a vray.Vector that represent an affine transformation. It supports mathematical operations like multiplication and addition; equality comparison; indexing, where the matrix is [0] and the offset [1].

Transform() -> new Transform with matrix and offset initialized to 0 Transform(matrix, offset) -> new Transform from vray.Matrix and vray.Vector

matrix¶

The rotation & scale matrix

offset¶

The translation vector

class vray.VRMat¶

Bases: object

V-Ray VRMat

This class groups a few functions for work with .vrmat (.vismat) materials.

VRMat(fileName[, pluginPath]) -> create a new VRMat object for the specified
file. The optional path is for cases where vray_MtlVRmat.dll/so is at a non-standard location.
getDecodedThumbnail()¶

Returns the the material thumbnail with the given name contained in the file as buffer/memview.

getEncodedThumbnail()¶

Returns the the material thumbnail with the given name contained in the file as a Base64 encoded PNG.

getMaterialList()¶

Returns a list of material names contained in the file.

class vray.VRayImage¶

Bases: object

V-Ray Image

Contains raw image data in full 32-bit floating point format. Methods allow for some basic image manipulation and saving to popular 8-bit image file formats. Supports buffer and memoryview protocol

addColor()¶

Adds the color to the image with blending. Positional arguments:

color, Color or AColor - the color to add to each pixel

Returns True on success.

changeContrast()¶

Changes the image contrast by the specified value (-1, 1). Positional arguments:

contrast, float - normalized contrast change factor

Returns True on success.

changeExposure()¶

Increases the image exposure by the specified exposure value (EV). Positional arguments:

ev, float - target EV difference

Returns True on success.

changeGamma()¶

Applies the specified gamma correction to the image. Positional arguments:

gamma, float - reciprocal of the exponent to apply to each pixel’s color

Returns True on success.

compress()¶

Compresses a V-Ray Image and returns its memoryview. Positional (in this order) or keyword arguments, all optional:

quality, int - image quality value (1-9 for png, 1-99 for jpeg) preserveAlpha, bool - whether to keep the alpha channel (PNG, BMP). Defaults to false swapChannels, bool - by default RGBA, but if True swap to BGRA type, string - file type renderer, VRayRenderer - if passed, it will be used to output errors
createFromBuffer()¶

Creates a new VRayImage from a bytearray

crop()¶

Creates a new VRayImage from a region in the source one. Positional (in this order) or keyword arguments, all obligatory:

x, int - left border pixel coordinate (in image space) of the crop region y, int - top border pixel coordinate (in image space) of the crop region width, int - pixel width of the crop region height, int - pixel height of the crop region
cutIn()¶

Creates a new downscaled VRayImage preserving source aspect ratio, touching the specified rectangle from outside and cropping the new image to fit the rectangle.Positional (in this order) or keyword arguments, all obligatory:

width, int - target width in pixels height, int - target height in pixels
downscale()¶

Creates a new downscaled VRayImage. Positional (in this order) or keyword arguments, all obligatory:

width, int - target width in pixels height, int - target height in pixels
downscaleCropped()¶

Creates a new downscaled VRayImage from a region in the source one. Positional (in this order) or keyword arguments, all obligatory:

x, int - left border pixel coordinate (in image space) of the croped source region y, int - top border pixel coordinate (in image space) of the croped source region srcWidth, int - pixel width of the cropped source region srcHeight, int - pixel height of the croped source region dstWidth, int - target width in pixels dstHeight, int - target height in pixels
draw()¶

Draws a V-Ray Image over the current image. Positional (in this order) or keyword arguments:

image, VRayImage - the source image x, optional int - left pixel index from where to draw y, optional int - top pixel index from where to draw

Returns True on success.

fitIn()¶

Creates a new downscaled VRayImage preserving source aspect ratio and touching the specified rectangle from inside. Positional (in this order) or keyword arguments, all obligatory:

width, int - target width in pixels height, int - target height in pixels
fitOut()¶

Creates a new downscaled VRayImage preserving source aspect ratio and touching the specified rectangle from outside. Positional (in this order) or keyword arguments, all obligatory:

width, int - target width in pixels height, int - target height in pixels
height¶

Pixel height of this object.

host¶

Host name that produced the image, if available.

makeNegative()¶

Makes this a negative image. In other words, replaces colors with their complementary colors.

save()¶

Saves VRayImage to file. Format is deduced from the extension. Positional (in this order) or keyword arguments, all optional:

fileName, string - relative or absolute file path and name quality, int - image quality value (1-9 for png, 1-99 for jpeg) preserveAlpha, bool - whether to keep the alpha channel (PNG, BMP). Defaults to true swapChannels, bool - by default RGBA, but if True swap to BGRA type, string - file type renderer, VRayRenderer - if passed, it will be used to output errors

Returns True on success.

toBitmapData()¶

Creates a buffer (memoryview) and fills it with the raw pixel data scaled to 8-bit integers. Positional (in this order) or keyword arguments, all optional:

preserveAlpha, bool - whether to keep the alpha channel. Defaults to false swapChannels, bool - by default RGBA, but if True swap to BGRA reverseY, bool - if true, invert the vertical scanline order stride, int - the byte stride between the first pixel of each row
width¶

Pixel width of this object.

x¶

Bucket horizontal (left) position.

y¶

Bucket vertical (top) position.

class vray.VRayRenderer¶

Bases: object

V-Ray Renderer

This is the main object in V-Ray. It contains scene data and provides various methods for rendering control. It is the ‘client’ side in distributed rendering, where multiple servers can be attached (both AppSDK VRayServer objects and V-Ray Standalone processes).

VRayRenderer() optional constructor arguments:
renderMode, string - see VRayRenderer.renderMode (default ‘rtCpu’) imageWidth, int - output image width. If <=0 use SettingsOutput.img_width from the scene imageHeight, int - output image height. If <=0 use SettingsOutput.img_height from the scene rtSampleLevel, int - maximum number of sampling passes in RT mode (0=infinite, default) rtNoiseThreshold, float - noise level at which to stop in RT mode (between 0 and 1, usually 0.1-0.001; 0 = no threshold - default) rtTimeout, int - maximum time to render in RT mode, milliseconds (0=infinite, default) numThreads, int - CPU threads to use for rendering or all available if 0 (default) enableFrameBuffer, bool - whether to initialize VFB GUI (default True) showFrameBuffer, bool - whether to show the VFB when rendering starts (default True) inProcess, bool - whether to use this process for rendering or DR only if False (default True) keepRTRunning, bool - if a noise/time/sample limit is reached in RT, don’t stop (default False) transferAssets, bool - allow network transfer of assets to DR servers (default True) useCachedAssets, bool - allow DR servers to use cached assets from previous sessions (default True) bakeGamma, bool - True to bake the gamma in VRayImages, False (default) to keep them in linear space noRenderLicensePreCheck, bool - skip checking render license at construction time (default False) noDR, bool - set to True to disable DR ability. This will reduce memory usage (default False) pluginLibraryPath, string - alternative location for V-Ray plugins gpuPluginPath, string - alternative location for V-Ray CUDA/OpenCL plugin autoCommit, bool - see VRayRenderer.autoCommit (default True) vfbDrawStyle, string - one of ‘auto’, ‘standalone’, ‘3dsMax’, ‘3dsMaxQt’, ‘maya’ (default auto)
addHosts()¶

Adds V-Ray servers to the current renderer.

Argument: list/tuple of host names or ip:port strings Return values:

-2 - Failed to resolve hostname -1 - Renderer is invalid or in the PREPARING state

0 - Hosts were added to the list, but failed to connect 1 - Hosts were successfully added and connected if rendering was in progress 2 - Hosts were successfully added to the list, but weren’t connected due to lack of work

Note: Connection is not established until rendering starts

append()¶

Appends a vrscene file to the current scene. Blocking call.

Arguments:
filename, string

The file is loaded without wiping the current scene. This is similar to the #include directive in vrscene files. The appendFiltered() method is even more useful as it can discard unwanted parts of the scene being appended.

appendAsText()¶

Appends a vrscene from text string. Blocking call.

Arguments:
sceneContent, string - text that is in valid vrscene syntax

Same as append() but reads directly from memory.

appendAsTextFiltered()¶

Appends a vrscene from a text string using a plugin filtering callback. Blocking call.

Arguments:
sceneContent, string - text that is in valid vrscene syntax filter, function(string, string)->string
Filter callback:
pluginType - the plugin class type instanceName - the original instance name

The callback should return the name of the instance if it is to be kept or None if it should be discarded. The returned name can be modified.

appendFiltered()¶
autoCommit¶

Apply changes to renderer immediately if True (default). Otherwise changes are applied only when commit() is called. This is useful for large batches of changes because it is more efficient to apply them all at once.

bucketRenderNearest()¶

Render buckets closer to the specified (x, y) position first.

This is the same as enabling VFB ‘follow mouse cursor’ and pointing at this point.

camera¶

Get/set current camera plugin. This only matters in DR.

classes¶

Returns a dictionary of V-Ray classes (plugin types).

clearAllPropertyValuesUpToTime()¶

Removes all values from animated properties with keyframe times less than or equal to the given time.

close()¶

Closes the renderer. Releases licenses. The object is unusable after this call.

closed¶

Renderer already closed and unusable if true.

commit()¶

Commits any previously introduced but not committed changes.

If autoCommit was False, any plugin and property changes are queued up and this call flushes them, changing the rendered image. Argument: force, bool - don’t delay the commit. Shouldn’t be necessary. Returns True if the changes are successfully applied.

continueSequence()¶

Resumes sequence rendering with the next frame.

createCombinedProxyFileMesh()¶

Creates a vrmesh file from data stored in multiple GeomStaticMesh plugins.

Keyword arguments:
geomPlugins - Obligatory. A list of GeomStaticMesh plugin instances filled with the geometry data. file - Obligatory. Destination filename (.vrmesh format). transforms - Optional. A list of Transform objects for transforming the vertices and normals in 3D space. Must match the geomPlugins list. voxelElements - Optional. Target number of triangles in each voxel. numPreviewElements - Optional. Number of preview triangles to generate. previewType - Optional. One of ‘face_sampling’, ‘clustering’, ‘edge_collapse’ or ‘combined’ (default). isAnimated - Optional. True if the mesh is animated. startFrame - Optional. Where to start exporting the animation from. endFrame - Optional. Where to stop exporting the animation.
createProxyFileMesh()¶

Creates a .vrmesh file from data stored in a GeomStaticMesh plugin.

Keyword arguments:
geomPlugin - Obligatory. A GeomStaticMesh plugin instance filled with the geometry data. file - Obligatory. Destination filename (.vrmesh format). transform - Optional. A Transform object for transforming the vertices and normals in 3D space. voxelElements - Optional. Target number of triangles in each voxel. numPreviewElements - Optional. Number of preview triangles to generate. previewType - Optional. One of ‘face_sampling’, ‘clustering’, ‘edge_collapse’ or ‘combined’ (default). isAnimated - Optional. True if the mesh is animated. startFrame - Optional. Where to start exporting the animation from. endFrame - Optional. Where to stop exporting the animation.
cropRegion¶
Returns or sets the crop region as a tuple or a dictionary (empty to reset):
(srcWidth, srcHeight, rgnLeft, rgnTop, rgnWidth, rgnHeight)

The tuple defines a virtual crop region (rgnLeft, rgnTop, rgnWidth, rgnHeight) within a virtual source image space with size srcWidth, srcHeight. Image output size is unchanged (VRayRenderer.size)

denoiseNow()¶

Run denoiser immediately.

The scene must contain a RenderChannelDenoiser instance that supplies the parameters. Returns True if denoising was successfully started asynchronously and False if the renderer state or denoising parameters are inappropriate. When denoising is done the postEffectsUpdated callback will be called.

export()¶

Exports the scene to a .vrscene file. Blocking call.

Arguments:
filename, string - the target output file name options, dict - export options, see below. Can be omitted entirely or partially

Returns True on success. Options:

compressed, bool - whether to compress lists of numbers (default True) useHexFormat, bool - whether to use hex format for lists of numbers (default True) framesInSeparateFiles, bool - whether to save separate files for animated values (default False) renderElementsSeparateFolders, bool - whether to save render elements to separate folders (default False) subFileInfos, list/tuple of dicts (see below) - used to split the scene into separate files based on plugin categories
SubFileInfo dict:
type, string - one of ‘view’, ‘lights’, ‘geometry’, ‘nodes’, ‘materials’, ‘textures’, ‘bitmaps’, ‘render_elements’ suffix, string - a suffix for the file name (before extension) of this part of the scene
frame¶

Frame number (int) to render when NOT in sequence mode. Also affects keyframes when setting animated property values. See useAnimatedValues. Current frame and current time are related through the ‘fps’ property of SettingsOutput.

getActiveHosts()¶

Returns all active V-Ray servers attached to the current renderer.

getAllHosts()¶

Returns all V-Ray servers attached to the current renderer.

getBoundingBox()¶

Returns the whole scene bounding box excluding infinite primitives.

getComputeDevicesCUDA()¶

Returns a list of dicts describing the available devices for CUDA rendering.

The “C++/CPU” device uses the CUDA engine code compiled for the x86-64 architecture. It is not the CPU V-Ray engine. It is disabled by default but you can enable it for faster “hybrid” rendering.

getComputeDevicesOpenCL()¶

Returns a list of dicts describing the available devices for OpenCL rendering.

getImage()¶

Returns a copy the current image as VRayImage.

Keyword (or positional in this order) arguments, all optional:
left, int - left pixel border of the region to get (default 0) top, int - top pixel border of the region to get (default 0) width, int - width of the region to get (default full width) height, int - height of the region to get (default full width) doColorCorrect, bool - if True, VFB color corrections will be applied (default False)
getInactiveHosts()¶

Returns all inactive V-Ray servers attached to the current renderer.

getRTStatistics()¶

Returns RT renderer statistics: ‘paths per second’, ‘elapsed ticks’ and ‘sample level’.

height¶

Returns or sets the output image height.

imageReady¶

Returns True if rendering process has finished. There could be an error. Check if VRayRenderer.state equals vray.RENDERER_STATE_IDLE_DONE to make sure rendering completed successfully.

load()¶

Loads a vrscene file. Blocking call.

Arguments:
filename, string

Any previous scene contents are wiped. An exception is thrown if loading fails.

loadAsText()¶

Loads a vrscene from text string. Blocking call.

Arguments:
sceneContent, string - text that is in valid vrscene syntax

Same as load() but reads directly from memory.

loadAsTextFiltered()¶
loadFiltered()¶
options¶

Gets/sets current renderer options dictionary.

pause()¶

Pauses RT rendering.

paused¶

Returns whether RT rendering is paused. See VRayRenderer.pause and VRayRenderer.resume.

pickPlugin()¶

Return the first scene Node object intersected at the given pixel.

Arguments:
x, int - coordinate y, int - coordinate timeout, optional int - maximum time to perform the intersection

The return value is a vray.Plugin (of type Node) or None.

plugins¶

Returns a dictionary of V-Ray plugin instances.

readProxyPreviewGeometry()¶

Read simplified geometry preview data from a proxy file (.vrmesh, .abc)

Keyword (and positional in this order) arguments:
proxyPlugin, plugin - A GeomMeshFile plugin instance to read the file path and parameters from countHint, int - An optional number of triangles to return. The exact number of elements in ‘vertices’ may differ slightly

If countHint is not specified, proxyPlugin.num_preview_faces is used. Returns a tuple (vertices, indices) or None on failure:

vertices, VectorList - Output vertex preview data. The array can be passed on directly to DirectX/OpenGL etc. (and the indices too) indices, IntList - Output face index data. Each three consecutive elements in make up one triangle
readProxyPreviewHair()¶

Read simplified hair preview data from a proxy file (.vrmesh, .abc)

Keyword (and positional in this order) arguments:
proxyPlugin, plugin - A GeomMeshFile plugin instance to read the file path and parameters from countHint, int - The number of hair strands to return. The exact number of elements in ‘lengths’ may differ slightly

If countHint is not specified, proxyPlugin.num_preview_faces is used. Returns a tuple (vertices, lengths) or None on failure:

vertices, VectorList - Output vertex preview data. Consecutive vertices form hair strands. The i-th strand has lengths[i] consecutive vertices lengths, FloatList - Output hair strand length data. Each strand can have a different number of vertices
readProxyPreviewParticles()¶

Read simplified particle preview data from a proxy file (.vrmesh, .abc)

Keyword (and positional in this order) arguments:
proxyPlugin, plugin - A GeomMeshFile plugin instance to read the file path and parameters from countHint, int - An optional number of particles to return. The exact number of elements in ‘positions’ may differ slightly

If countHint is not specified, proxyPlugin.num_preview_faces is used. Returns a positions list or None on failure:

positions, VectorList - Output particle preview data. The positions of the preview subset of all particles.
removeHosts()¶

Removes V-Ray servers from the current renderer.

Argument: list/tuple of host names or ip:port strings

renderElements¶

Returns render elements wrapper object.

renderMode¶
Gets/sets current render mode. One of these strings, case insensitive:
‘production’ - CPU rendering optimized for final image results ‘productionCuda’ - GPU rendering optimized for final image results using CUDA ‘productionOpenCL’ - GPU rendering optimized for final image results using OpenCL ‘rtCpu’ - interactive CPU rendering allowing fast feedback after scene changes ‘rtGpuCuda’ - interactive GPU CUDA rendering allowing fast feedback after scene changes ‘rtGpuOpenCL’ - interactive GPU OpenCL rendering allowing fast feedback after scene changes

CUDA modes require an nVidia GPU and recent drivers. OpenCL modes requires a compatible OpenCL driver Mode can’t be changed while rendering, but it can be changed without wiping the scene.

renderRegion¶

Returns or sets the render region as a tuple or a dictionary (empty to reset): (left, top, width, height)

renderSequence()¶

Begins rendering an animation sequence in a separate thread. A non-blocking call.

Argument:
frames, complex list/tuple - elements are either simple frame numbers or dicts described below or a mix
Frame range dict:
start, int - first frame of the sub-sequence end, int - last frame of the sub-sequence step, int - frame index incrementation step
reset()¶

Removes all plugins and resets the renderer. Takes the same arguments as the VRayRenderer constructor.

resume()¶

Resumes RT rendering.

saveCausticsFile()¶

Saves the caustics with the specified filename. Returns false if an error ocurred or there is no data to save

saveImage()¶

Saves the current image directly to file.

This call is equivalent to using the VFB save button and supports the same formats. Arguments:

filename, string - target file name. The extension determines the format. options, dict - save options, see below. Can be omitted entirely or partially

Returns True on success. Options dict:

skipAlpha, bool - do not write the alpha channel into a separate file frameNumber, bool - the current frame number will be appended to the file name(s) noAlpha, bool - do not write the alpha channel together with the color data singleChannel, bool - only a single channel is written to the file (the current one in vfb) skipRGB, bool - do not write the RGB channel into a separate file writeIntegerIDs, bool - (EXR only) write to EXR as integer data multiChannel, bool - create a single multi-channel file if the file format supports it applyColorCorrections, bool - bake the VFB color corrections to the output file compressionType, string - (EXR only) one of ‘noCompression’, ‘runLength’, ‘zipScanline’, ‘zipBlock’, ‘piz’, ‘pxr24’ bitsPerChannel, int - (EXR only) either 16 or 32
saveIrradianceMapFile()¶

Saves the irradiance map with the specified filename. Returns false if an error ocurred or there is no data to save

saveLightCacheFile()¶

Saves the light cache with the specified filename. Returns false if an error ocurred or there is no data to save

savePhotonMapFile()¶

Saves the photon map with the specified filename. Returns false if an error ocurred or there is no data to save

sequenceDone¶

Rendering of a sequence is finished if true.

sequenceFrame¶

Returns the current sequence frame number.

serializeScene()¶

Serializes the whole scene (plugins with their property values) contained in the renderer into a single memory stream no matter if they originate from a loaded or appended vrscene file or are created by code. The whole stream will be always transferred when DR hosts are connected. No DR hosts should have been connected before serialization. (Currently only one type of serialization is supported but other types may be added in the future.) This method is here mainly for debug purposes but it can be helpful in some other cases as well.

Do not use it unless you know exactly what you’re doing.
setComputeDevicesCUDA()¶

Pass a list if devices indices (matching the getComputeDevicesCUDA list) to use for CUDA rendering.

setComputeDevicesOpenCL()¶

Pass a list if devices indices (matching the getComputeDevicesOpenCL list) to use for OpenCL rendering.

setImprovedDefaults()¶

Initializes some settings plugins to recommended values. Call on an empty scene before your own changes.

setOnBucketFailed()¶

Sets a callback to be executed when rendering of a bucket has failed.

Callback arguments:
renderer, VRayRenderer - the renderer object that produced the event image, VRayImage - an empty image that contains the x,y,width,height and hostname of the bucket
setOnBucketInit()¶

Sets a callback to be executed when a new bucket has started rendering.

Callback arguments:
renderer, VRayRenderer - the renderer object that produced the event image, VRayImage - an empty image that contains the x,y,width,height and hostname of the bucket
setOnBucketReady()¶

Sets a callback to receive completed buckets from production rendering.

Callback arguments:
renderer, VRayRenderer - the renderer object that produced the event image, VRayImage - a small image with only this rendered bucket
setOnDumpMessage()¶

Sets a callback to receive text messages from V-Ray.

V-Ray produces many messages of different types during rendering. It is very useful to display them or at least save them to a log file for detecting and diagnosing issues etc. Callback arguments:

renderer, VRayRenderer - the renderer object that produced the event message, string - the message text, no newline included level, int - defines the type of the message within one of the below ranges
Level ranges:
0-9999 - errors 10000-19999 - warnings 20000-29999 - normal info >= 30000 - debug
setOnImageReady()¶

Sets a callback to be executed when rendering is finished.

Important: this gets called even when rendering is not finished successfully. You can check the cause with the VRayRenderer.state property. Callback arguments:

renderer, VRayRenderer - the renderer object that produced the event
setOnPostEffectsUpdated()¶

Sets a callback to be executed when a post-processed image is available.

Lens effects and Denoising can be performed periodically during rendering and this callback allows you to get the images from the prespective channel when they are ready. Callback arguments:

renderer, VRayRenderer - the renderer object that produced the event
setOnProgress()¶

Sets a callback to receive progress increments for the current V-Ray task.

This is usually used to implement a progress bar. Callback arguments:

renderer, VRayRenderer - the renderer object that produced the event title, string - title of the ongoing task workDone, int - number of work items done workTotal, int - total number of work items in the current task
setOnRenderLast()¶

Sets a callback to be executed when the RenderLast button in VFB has been pressed.

The button does nothing by default. You can call start here. Callback arguments:

renderer, VRayRenderer - the renderer object that produced the event isRendering, bool - whether there was a rendering in progress when the button was pressed
setOnRenderStart()¶

Sets a callback to be executed when rendering starts.

Rendering is considered started when all loading and preparation tasks are complete. This can take considerable time with complex scenes. Any renderer modifications are blocked between starting and this event. Callback arguments:

renderer, VRayRenderer - the renderer object that produced the event
setOnRenderViewChanged()¶

Sets a callback to be executed when the ‘transform’ or ‘fov’ property of RenderView has been changed.

This can be used to intercept user camera control through the VFB. Callback arguments:

renderer, VRayRenderer - the renderer object that produced the event propName, string - name of the RenderView property that has been changed
setOnRtImageUpdated()¶

Sets a callback to receive a new image from progressive rendering when available.

This applies to both RT rendering and Production rendering with the progressive image sampler despite the name of this event (legacy). You should be careful with processing the image within the callback because this would block the event queue if the calculations are heavy. See also setRTImageUpdateDifference() and setRTImageUpdateTimeout(). Callback arguments:

renderer, VRayRenderer - the renderer object that produced the event image, VRayImage - a copy of the image as rendered at the time of the event
setOnSequenceDone()¶

Sets a callback to be executed when an animation sequence rendering is finished.

This is similar to onImageReady, but only occurs rendering sequences. It only occurs after the last frame is done, while onImageReady occurs for every finished frame in the sequence. Callback arguments:

renderer, VRayRenderer - the renderer object that produced the event
setOnSequenceStart()¶

Sets a callback to be executed when an animation sequence rendering starts.

This is similar to onRenderStart, but only occurs when renderSequence is used. Callback arguments:

renderer, VRayRenderer - the renderer object that produced the event
setOnVFBClosed()¶

Sets a callback to be executed when the close button in VFB is pressed.

Callback arguments:
renderer, VRayRenderer - the renderer object that produced the event
setRTImageUpdateDifference()¶

Sets the maximum difference threshold between two intermediate images returned by V-Ray RT

This criterion determines when to send the current image in the callback event. This helps prevent too many callback events for very small image changes. Default value: 2.0

setRTImageUpdateTimeout()¶

Sets the maximum interval in milliseconds between image events in V-Ray RT rendering

When the timeout elapses the current image is sent to the callback even if the difference criteria is not met. Default value: 0 (disabled)

setResumableRendering()¶

Enable or disable resumable production rendering

Keyword (and positional in this order) arguments:
enable, obligatory boolean outputFile, optional string - resumable file name. Obligatory if SettingsOutput.img_file is not set compressProgressiveFiles, optional bool - whether to compress .vrprog file when rendering with progressive sampling progressiveAutoSaveSeconds, optional int - how often to save a checkpoint when rendering with progressive sampling

This has to be called before starting a render

size¶

Returns or sets the output image size as a tuple.

start()¶

Begins rendering in a separate thread. A non-blocking call.

This first performs VRayRenderer.stop() internally. You have to wait for the onRenderStart event before being able to modify the renderer.

startSync()¶

Begins rendering in a separate thread. Blocks until the onRenderStart event.

This might take significant time for complex scenes.

state¶

Returns the current state of the renderer. Compare against vray.RENDERER_STATE_* constants.

stop()¶

Stops the rendering. This might block for some time.

time¶

The time (float) for animated properties. Current frame and current time are related through the ‘fps’ property of SettingsOutput.

useAnimatedValues¶

When this is True, setting property values will use the current ‘time’ or ‘frame’ to create keyframes for animation. Defaults to False.

vfb¶

Returns a VFB wrapper object with methods related to the VFB.

waitForImageReady()¶
waitForSequenceDone()¶

Waits for the rendering of an animation sequence to finish.

If a non-zero timeout value (in milliseconds) is passed, the wait is limited. Returns False in case of timeout or error.

width¶

Returns or sets the output image width.

class vray.VRayServer¶

Bases: object

V-Ray Server A server object for distributed rendering. It awaits connection from a client and serves render requests from it. Only one client at a time can be served. Server objects have to be in separate processes. They can’t be created in the same process as VRayRenderer client objects.

VRayServer() constructor optional keyword arguments:
portNumber, int - which port to accept connections on (defaults to 30304) numThreads, int - number of threads to use for rendering (0=all, default) remoteScenePath, string - filename (and path) for temporary scene file pluginLibraryPath, string - alternative location for V-Ray plugins gpuPluginPath, string - alternative location for V-Ray CUDA/OpenCL plugin noRenderLicensePreCheck, bool - skip checking license at construction time changeCurrentDirectory, bool - if True, chdir to remoteScenePath keepSceneInMemory, bool - do not write temporary vrscene file, keep all the data in memory overwriteLocalCacheSettings, bool - if True override the below two parameters with settings from the client cachedAssetsLimitType, int - 0=no limit for assets cache; 1=hour limit; 2=gigabyte limit cachedAssetsLimitValue, float - value in hours or GB when cachedAssetsLimitType is 1 or 2
close()¶

Closes the server. It can’t be used after this call.

closed¶

Server already closed if true.

options¶

Returnsa copy of the current server options dictionary.

run()¶

Runs the server in the current thread. A blocking call.

setOnConnect()¶

Sets a callback function to receive a notification when a renderer is connected to this server. The callback takes 1 argument:

hostname, string - the host name (or IP address) that connected.
setOnDisconnect()¶

Sets a callback function to receive a notification when a renderer is disconnected to this server. The callback takes 1 argument:

hostname, string - the host name (or IP address) that disconnected.
setOnDumpMessage()¶

Sets a callback function to receive text messages from VRayServer. The callback takes 2 arguments:

message, string - the text from V-Ray level, int - the severity of the message (error=0-9999, warning=10000-19999, info=20000-29999, debug>=30000)
setOnProgress()¶

Sets a callback function to receive the progression of VRayServer processing. The callback takes 3 arguments:

message, string - description of the currently performed render task progress, int - work units completed so far total, int - total number of work units for the current task
setOnStart()¶

Sets a callback function to receive a notification when rendering on this server starts. The callback takes 0 arguments.

start()¶

Starts the server in a separate thread. A non-blocking call.

stop()¶

Stops the server. It can be started again.

class vray.Vector¶

Bases: object

V-Ray Vector

A mathematical vector in 3D space. Supports the usual mathematical operations including dot and cross products (* and ^). The three components can be indexed like a list.

Vector() -> new Vector with value (0, 0, 0) Vector(x,y,z) -> new Vector initialized to (x,y,z)

lenSquared()¶

Returns the length of this vector squared.

x¶

Vector X axis value

y¶

Vector Y axis value

z¶

Vector Z axis value

vray.close()¶

(optional) Closes the V-Ray library and releases any licenses. You can’t use V-Ray after this call.

vray.enableFrameBuffer()¶

Enables or disables V-Ray frame buffer globally. If called before creating a renderer, this prevents initialization of the GUI component entirely There is a separate option ‘enableFrameBuffer’ for VRayRenderer that only affects the instance.

vray.encodeScannedMaterialParams()¶

Encodes the V-Ray scanned material parameters into a binary block to be used as a value of BRDFScanned.param_block property.

vray.getEnvVar()¶

Gets the value of an environment variable.

V-Ray uses environment variables to unlock some behaviors and it could be difficult to get them when the host process (Python) uses a runtime different from V-Ray’s, specifically on Windows. Argument: varName, string Returns the value or None if not set.

vray.getSDKVersion()¶

Returns the AppSDK version as a tuple.

vray.getSDKVersionDetails()¶

Returns the detailed AppSDK version as a string.

vray.getVRayVersion()¶

Returns the V-Ray Core version as a tuple.

vray.getVRayVersionDetails()¶

Returns the detailed V-Ray Core version as a string.

vray.setEnvVar()¶

Sets or removes an environment variable.

V-Ray uses environment variables to unlock some behaviors and it could be difficult to set them when the host process (Python) uses a runtime different from V-Ray’s, specifically on Windows. Arguments:

varName, string - the name of the variable varValue, string or None - if None the variable is deleted

Returns True if successfully set.

vray.setLicenseServers()¶

(optional) Sets the license server configuration with positional or keyword arguments. Use this if you don’t have a vrlclient.xml file or want to avoid it for some reason. Arguments:

(serverName, serverPort[, serverName1, serverPort1, serverName2, serverPort2, username, password]) where ports are integers and the rest are strings
Returns 0 on success or one of these error codes otherwise:
-1: You can’t change server settings while license is engaged -2: Cannot initialize authentication server. This is an internal error -3: Cannot find the appropriate method in vray.dll. This is most probably a version mismatch

Controls the amount of light kicked back from the hair in dual-scattering mode.

Controls the amount of light bleeding through the hair in dual-scattering mode.

type: float
Controls the rolloff of the caustic glints in the hair. Lower values make the glints more pingy, higher values make them softer and less apparent.
glint_strength¶
type: float
Strength of the caustic glints. Sensible values are in the range 1-5.
glossy_indirect_strength¶
type: float
melanin¶
type: TextureFloat
The melanin content of the hair fibre. Use this to generate natural colors for mammalian hair. 0 will give white hair, 0.2-04 blonde, 0.4-0.6 red, 0.6-0.8 brown and 0.8-1.0 black hair. If you want to set the color of the hair with a texture map, set this to 0 and use the Dye color parameter.
opacity¶
type: TextureFloat
random_hue¶
type: TextureFloat
Adds a random offest to the hue of the dye color.
random_melanin¶
type: TextureFloat
Adds a random offset to the melanin content of the hair. Values from 0.05 to 0.2 give a very natural color variation.
random_saturation¶
type: TextureFloat
Adds a random offest to the saturation of the Dye color.
random_tangent¶
type: TextureFloat
Adds a random offset to the hair tangent which can be useful for breaking up uniform-looking grooms. Note that this value is dependent on your scene scale.

type: TextureFloat
Offset on the shift of this lobe’s highlight.
specular2_strength¶
type: TextureFloat
specular2_width_scale¶
type: TextureFloat
Multiplier on the width of this lobe’s highlight.
specular_shift¶
type: float
How much the highlights are shifted along the hair by the cuticles on the hair fibre. Generally this wants to be 1 to 1.5 times the value of the Width parameter.
specular_width¶
type: float
The width of the hair highlights, essentially how shiny the hair appears. Values in the range 1-7 are sensible for human hair.
transmission_color¶
type: Texture
transmission_rolloff¶
type: float
Controls the rolloff of the transmission highlight. Essentially, if you want the transmission highlight to only appear when the light is directly behind the hair, set this value to 10 or lower. If you want to increase the amount the highlight spreads as the light comes around from behind, set this value higher than 10.

class plugins.EnvironmentFog¶
affect_background¶
type: boolean
When this option is off, the background will not be obscured by the fog.
affect_camera¶
type: boolean
Specifies if the fog will be visible to camera rays.
affect_gi¶
type: boolean
Specifies if the fog should affect GI rays.
affect_reflections¶
type: boolean
Specifies whether the fog will be rendered in reflections.
affect_refractions¶
type: boolean
Specifies whether the fog will be rendered in refractions.
affect_shadows¶
type: boolean
Specifies if the fog should affect shadow rays.
color¶
type: Color
Defines the color of the fog, when it is illuminated by light sources.
color_mult¶
type: float
Fog color multiplier
color_tex¶
type: Texture
Defines the color of the fog, when it is illuminated by light sources. You can also use a texture map to drive the fog color.
cutoff_threshold¶
type: float
Controls when the raymarcher will stop traversing the volume. If the accumulated volume transparency falls below this threshold, the volume will be considered opaque and tracing will be aborted. Higher values make the rendering faster but may introduce artifacts.
deep_output¶
type: boolean
Toggle the deep image output. Note that enabling this option will force ray marching even for simple volumetrics, which can cause slower rendering.
density¶
type: float
Fog density. A multiplier for the Fog distance parameter.
density_tex¶
type: TextureFloat
Texture for fog density. A multiplier for the Fog distance parameter that allows a texture to be used for the density of the fog.
distance¶
type: float
Distance between fog particles. Controls the fog density. Larger values make the fog more transparent, while smaller values make it more dense.
emission¶
type: Color
Fog emission color. Controls the fog emission (self-illumination). You can use this parameter to substitute the ambient illumination inside the fog, instead of using GI.
emission_mult¶
type: float
Fog emission multiplier.
emission_mult_tex¶
type: TextureFloat
Fog emission multiplier texture.
emission_tex¶
type: Texture
Fog emission texture. Controls the fog emission (self-illumination). You can use this parameter to substitute the ambient illumination inside the fog, instead of using GI.
enabled¶
type: boolean
If false, disable the rendering
fade_out_mode¶
type: int
fade out mode 0: Multiply by density, 1: Add density to falloff
fade_out_radius¶
type: float
fade out effect for the edges
gizmos¶
type: List<Object>
List of gizmos
height¶
type: float
Fog starting point along the up-axis. By default the up axis is Z.
ior¶
type: float
Index of refraction for the volume, which describes the way light bends when crossing the material surface. A value of 1.0 means the light will not change direction.
jitter¶
type: boolean
If true, add a random offset when starting sampling.
light_mode¶
type: int
light mode 0: no lights, 1: Use per-gizmo lights, 2: Override per-gizmo lights, 3: Intersect with per-gizmo lights, 4: Add to per-gizmo lights
lights¶
type: List<Object>
A list with lights. How they affect the fog depends on the ‘Light mode’ paramter as well.
max_steps¶
type: int
Maximum number of steps through the volume.
opacity_mode¶
type: boolean
If true, density will be treated as opacity.
per_object_fade_out_radius¶
type: boolean
fade out effect for the edges per object
scale¶
type: List<Float>
stretch aspect for the 3 axis, when the fog container must grow/shrink preserving its original density
scatter_bounces¶
type: int
Number of GI bounces calculated inside the fog.
scatter_gi¶
type: boolean
When on, the fog will also scatter global illumination. Note that this can be quite slow. In many cases, global illumination within the fog can be substituted with a simple emission term. When this option is on, the currently selected global illumination algorithm in the V-Ray settings will be used to accelerate GI inside the volume (e.g. the irradiance map, light cache, photon map or brute-force).
shadow_opacity¶
type: float
Volume opacity scale for shadow rays.
simplify_gi¶
type: boolean
Simplify global illumination. When this option is checked V-Ray will use a simplified method for calculating the GI when rendering parts of the fog that are textured or are being faded out.
solid_mode¶
type: boolean
If true, this will cause to disable randomization when sampling and take 1 sample at 0.5 density.
solid_threshold¶
type: float
Solid mode transparency threshold
step_size¶
type: float
Determines the size of one step through the volume. Smaller steps produce more accurate results but are slower to render. In general, dense volumes require smaller step sizes than more transparent volumes. In practice, step sizes that are two to three times smaller than the Fog distance parameter work well.
subdivs¶
type: int
This parameter determines the number of points inside the fog at which volumetric lighting is evaluated. Smaller values for this parameter render faster, but may produce noise in the image. Higher values render longer, but with less noise. It is only used when there are no texture maps specified, in which case the volume properties are the same everywhere.
tex_samples¶
type: int
Number of texture samples for each step through the volume. This allows to sample textures more accurately than the volumetric lighting. It is useful in cases where the textures vary much faster than the lighting itself (e.g. for detailed fractal textures).
use_height¶
type: boolean
Whether or not the height should be taken into account.
use_shade_data¶
type: boolean
True if the shade data should be used when sampling textures. The light mode will be ignored if this is true and the shader is not global!
use_shade_instance¶
type: boolean
True if the shade instance should be used when sampling textures.
yup¶
type: boolean
If true, y is the up axis, not z.

class plugins.GeomDisplacedMesh¶
cache_normals¶
type: boolean

type: boolean
Use to enable 2d displacement. Overrides the vector_displacement flag.

type: boolean
Enable or disable support for tiled textures (UDIM/UVTILE) when generating 2d displacement.

type: float
Determines the displacement amount for white areas in the displacement map; if use_globals is true this is multiplied by the global displacement amount option.

type: float
This constant value is added to the displacement map

type: Texture
The displacement texture
displacement_tex_float¶
type: TextureFloat
The displacement texture

The amount of UV space to average for filtering purposes. A value of 1.0 will average thw whole texture.

type: boolean
Filter the texture for 2d displacement.

type: int
This parameter overrides the imgWidth parameter from VRayFrameData during the calculation of the subdivision depth.

type: boolean
If true, the plugin will attempt to keep the continuity of the displaced surface.

type: int
The mapping channel to use for vector and 2d displacement.

type: Color
The biggest value for the displacement texture.

type: Object
The triangle mesh that will be displaced
min_bound¶
type: Color
The lowest value for the displacement texture.

type: boolean
If true, the parent transformation will affect the amount of displacement. Used only when doing 3D displacement.
precision¶
type: int
Increase for curved surfaces to avoid artifacts.
resolution¶
type: int
Resolution at which to sample the displacement map for 2d displacement.
static_displacement¶
type: boolean
If true, the resulting triangles of the displacement algorithm will be inserted into the rayserver as static geometry.
tight_bounds¶
type: boolean
When this is on, initialization will be slower, but tighter bounds will be computed for the displaced triangles making rendering faster.
use_bounds¶
type: boolean
If true, the min/max values for the displacement texture are specified by the min_bound and max_bound parameters; if false, these are calculated automatically.
use_globals¶
type: boolean
If true, the global displacement quality settings will be used.
vector_displacement¶
type: int
When this is 1, the red, green and blue channels of displacement_tex_color will be used to perform vector displacement with base 0.5; if this is 2, then the map matches the Mudbox displacement maps.
view_dep¶
type: boolean
If use_globals is false, this determines if view-dependent tesselation is used.
water_level¶
type: float
Geometry below this displacement level will be clipped away.

class plugins.GeomMayaHair¶
colors¶
type: List<Color>
Color values for each hair vertex.Should have the same number of elements as hair_vertices.

If true, V-Ray will generate a W mapping coordinate that represents the position of the shaded point along the hair strands.

Manual control over the number of subdivisions when intersecting the spline based hairs.

A list with the positions of the hair vertices in object space. The number of elements should be equal to the sum of the elements of the num_hair_vertices parameter.

Incandescence values for each hair vertex.Should have the same number of elements as hair_vertices.
map_channels¶
type: List
A list of mapping channels; each channel itself is a list of 4 elements - the channel index, number of knots per strand, the knots array (vectors) and channel name. Channel index 0 is used for UVW coordinates if and only if strand_uvw is not set.
min_pixel_width¶
type: float
Restricts the hair strands to not be thinner than the specified value, in pixels. The V-Ray hair shader will make the hairs more transparent instead to achieve the same density.
num_hair_vertices¶
type: List<Integer>
A list of the number of hair vertices, one for each hair strand.
opacity¶
type: float
The Maya hair shader does not allow for different transparency on each hair vertex. Instead it uses a single opacity parameter for all of them.
strand_uvw¶

UVW values for each hair strand.Should have the same number of elements as num_hair_vertices.
transparency¶

type: boolean
If true, the hair will be added to the global static hair tree.

type: List<Float>
The width of the hair strands at each vertex.Should have the same number of elements as hair_vertices.

type: boolean
If true, the widths parameter is in pixels, otherwise it is in world units.

type: boolean

class plugins.GeomStaticMesh¶

class plugins.GeomStaticSmoothedMesh¶
cache_normals¶
type: boolean
If this option is equal to 1 then the normals of the generated triangles are cached. It has effect only if the surface is displaced.
classic_catmark¶
type: boolean
If equal to 1 then the classical Catmull-Clark masks will be used for meshes which contain only quadrangles.
displacement_amount¶
type: float
Determines the displacement amount for white areas in the displacement map; if use_globals is true this is multiplied by the global displacement amount option.
displacement_shift¶
type: float
This constant value is added to the displacement map
displacement_tex_color¶
type: Texture
The displacement texture
displacement_tex_float¶
type: TextureFloat
The displacement texture
edge_length¶
type: float
If use_globals is false, this determines the approximate edge length for the sub-triangles.
image_width¶
type: int
This parameter overrides the imgWidth paramter from VRayFrameData during the calculation of the subdivision depth.
keep_continuity¶
type: boolean
If true, the plugin will attempt to keep the continuity of the displaced surface
map_channel¶
type: int
The mapping channel to use for vector displacement.
max_bound¶
type: Color
The biggest value for the displacement texture
max_subdivs¶
type: int
If use_globals is false, this determines the maximum subdivisions for a triangle of the original mesh.
mesh¶
type: Object
The triangle mesh that will be displaced
min_bound¶
type: Color
The lowest value for the displacement texture
object_space_displacement¶
type: boolean
If true, the parent transformation will affect the amount of displacement. Used only when doing 3D displacement.
preserve_map_borders¶
type: int
The valid values are: -1 - not set; 0 - none; 1 - internal; 2 - all
static_subdiv¶
type: boolean
True if the resulting triangles of the subdivision algorithm will be inserted into the rayserver as static geometry.
use_bounds¶
type: boolean
If true, the min/max values for the displacement texture are specified by the min_bound and max_bound parameters; if false, these are calculated automatically.
use_globals¶
type: boolean
If true, the global displacement quality settings will be used.
vector_displacement¶
type: int
When this is 1, the red, green and blue channels of displacement_tex_color will be used to perform vector displacement with base 0.5; if this is 2, then the map matches the Mudbox displacement maps in absolute tangent space; 3 - vector displacement in object space.
view_dep¶
type: boolean
If use_globals is false, this determines if view-dependent tesselation is used.
water_level¶
type: float
Geometry below this displacement level will be clipped away

instances¶
type: List
A list of N+1 elements where N is the number of instances; the first element is a time value, the rest are lists with elements: particle id, transform, velocity transform, hasInstanceTime, instanceTime, additional_params_flags, additional_param_1, ..., additional_param_N, visibility, node, node, node, ...

type: List<Float>

type: List<Float>
Per-particle opacity.
shading_needs_ids¶
type: boolean
Set to true if the particle shade data sent to the instanced geometry needs to include the particle ID.
use_additional_params¶
type: boolean
If this is set to ‘true’ the lists in the ‘instances’ parameter have additional parameters after ‘time instancing’ parameters - an int with flags indicating what parameters follow and after that the parameters that follow. Their types depend on the flags in the int and are in a strictly defined order. New flags may be added and additional parameters for them can be added at the end of the chain. The flags are defined in HierarchicalParameterizedNodeParameters in an enum.
use_time_instancing¶
type: boolean
If this is set to ‘true’ the ‘instances’ parameter will contain the elements hasInstanceTime (bool) and instanceTime (double). Otherwise, they should not be present.
use_visibility¶
type: boolean
Use particle visibility. If set to ‘true’ the lists in the ‘instances’ parameter have particle visibility parameter after ‘additional parameters’.

Corresponds to Maya’s userVector1PP.

Specular contribution for the light.

type: boolean
When this option is on and GI calculation is set to Irradiance map V-Ray will calculate the effects of this light and store them in the irradiance map. The result is that the irradiance map is computed more slowly but the rendering takes less time. You can also save the irradiance map and reuse it later.

A color texture that if present will override the shadowColor parameter

type: int
The shape of the beam (0 - circular, 1 - rectangular, 2 - smooth rectangular)
specular_contribution¶
type: float
Specular contribution for the light.
storeWithIrradianceMap¶
type: boolean
When this option is on and GI calculation is set to Irradiance map V-Ray will calculate the effects of this light and store them in the irradiance map. The result is that the irradiance map is computed more slowly but the rendering takes less time. You can also save the irradiance map and reuse it later.

class plugins.MtlVRmat¶
filename¶
type: String
A .vrmat, .vismat or .vrscene file
mtlname¶
type: String
Which material tree to use. Top-level <Asset> name or MtlSingleBRDF name if .vrscene
param_override¶
type: String
(xml only) Override for a specific instance of a parameter. Requires full asset path plus ‘/paramname’.

Simple values and r/g/b/a tags are supported. Multiple overrides can be specified with colons. Example: “/Paint/Diffuse/color=<r>0.8</r><g>0.4</g><b>0.4</b>;/Paint/Diffuse/roughness=0.8”

param_override_all¶
type: String
(xml only) Override for all instances of a parameter. Requires only plugin type plus ‘/paramname’.

Simple values and r/g/b/a tags are supported. Multiple overrides can be specified with colons. Example: “MtlASGVIS/bump_units=1;BitmapBuffer/color_space=2”

Makes the material appear as a matte material, which shows the background, instead of the base material, when viewed directly.
maya_background_shader_compatibility¶
type: boolean
Setting this to true will make the matte alpha opaque so that the alpha of objects behind the matte won’t be seen.
no_gi_on_other_mattes¶
type: boolean
This will cause the material to appear as a matte object in reflections, refractions, GI etc for other matte objects.

fire_opacity_mode¶
type: int
0 - Use Smoke Opacity - fire will use the same opacity that is set in the ‘Smoke Opacity’ rollout. This way there will be no emission in cells where there is no smoke.

1 - Fully Visible - fire will always use ‘Opacity Multiplier’, regardless of the smoke opacity. 2 - Use Own Opacity - the Fire Luminance Gradient is used to determine the opacity.

oceanextramargin¶
type: float
The ocean is generated only in the camera view, which can lead to problems when using camera motion blur, using reflections, or when the ocean casts shadows on objects underwater. This option allows you to extend the ocean further from the borders of the camera view in order to solve such issues. The parameter is in % of the image size.

class plugins.RenderChannelDenoiser¶
enableDeepOutput¶
type: boolean
enabled¶
type: boolean
True to enable the denoising render element.
generate_render_elements¶
type: int
Specify what render elements to add to the rendered image. ‘Manual’ adds only the noise level and defocus amount elements; the rest must be added manually. ‘Depending on denoiser type’ adds only the elements needed for the chosen denoiser type (one-pass or by render elements). ‘All’ adds all elements that could be required by the denoiser and allows switching between the different types.
mode¶
type: int
The way the denoiser operates - only generate the needed render elements without running the denoiser, hide the channel with the denoised result in VFB, or show the channel with the denoised result in VFB.
name¶
type: String
The name of the render element containing the denoised image.
preset¶
type: int
Set the strength and radius to a few predefined values: 0.5/5 for mild denoising, 1/10 for default denoising, and 2/15 for strong denoising. Set to custom to enable the ‘strength’ and ‘radius’ parameters.
progressive_update¶
type: int
The frequency of updates during progressive rendering; roughly the percentage of time denoising is allowed to take compared to total render time. Zero disables updates during progressive rendering; larger values cause the denoiser to be updated more often; 100 causes update as often as possible. Values of 5 to 10 are usually sufficient.
radius¶
type: float
The pixel radius within which to look for similar pixel blocks. Larger values are slower, but may produce smoother results. Lower values are faster but may produce blotches. This value does not affect the strength of the denoising. A value of 10 is sufficient for most cases.
strength¶
type: float
The main denoiser control. Lower values modify the original image less, but may fail to clean up noise. Larger values are more effective at denoising, but may cause loss of detail. 0.5 is for mild denoising, 1.0 for normal strength and 2.0 for strong denoising.
type¶
type: int
Denoising can be calculated either as a single pass on the RGB image (faster with better noise removal but may blur texture details), or separately on the various render elements which are then combined into the final result (slower, may fail to clean up some kinds of noise, but preserves texture detail better). When denoising elements separately, the presence of color mapping may cause the brightness of the denoised result to be different than the computed RGB.
use_gpu¶
type: boolean
Enable usage of GPU version if OpenCL support is found.

Texture used for render mask when render_mask_mode=Texture.This accepts float textures, where a value of <=1e-6, means that V-Ray won’t render in this pixel
subdivision_edges¶
type: boolean
subdivision_jitter¶
type: boolean
If this is true, samples will be displaced randomly, for better AA of nearly horizontal or vertical edges.
subdivision_maxRate¶
type: int
Determines the maximum sampling rate for the adaptive subdivision sampler. A value of 0 means that samples will be one pixel apart. Positive values will put samples inside the pixels, while negative values will space the samples over several pixels.
subdivision_minRate¶
type: int
Determines the minimum sampling rate for the adaptive subdivision sampler. A value of 0 means that samples will be one pixel apart. Positive values will put samples inside the pixels, while negative values will space the samples over several pixels.
subdivision_normals¶
type: boolean
subdivision_normals_threshold¶
type: float
subdivision_threshold¶
type: float
type¶
type: int
The type of the image sampler (0 - fixed rate, 1 - adaptive, 2 - adaptive subdivision, 3 - progressive)

class plugins.SettingsLightCache¶
adaptive_sampling¶
type: boolean
True if adaptive hemispheric sampling should be used. This requires more memory than the non-adaptive light cache.
auto_save¶
type: boolean
True if the light cache should be saved at the end of the rendering.
auto_save_file¶
type: String
depth¶
type: int
Maximum bounces for the light cache. Leave this to the default value of 100. Note that, because of the way the light cache is calculated, the solution always converges to that of infinite light bounces, regardless of this value.
dont_delete¶
type: boolean
True if the light cache should not be deleted at the end of the rendering.
file¶
type: String
filter_samples¶
type: int
Number of samples to look for with the ‘nearest’ filter type.
filter_size¶
type: float
Filter size for the ‘fixed’ filter type.
filter_type¶
type: int
Filter type when reconstructing the illumination from the cache. 0 - no filter; 1 - nearest; 2 - fixed
mode¶
type: int
multiple_views¶
type: boolean
This causes the light cache to be calculated for the entire camera path, even when in single frame mode.
num_passes¶
type: int
Number of passes for the light cache. Each pass is rendered in a single thread, therefore it is best to set this to the number of processors.
prefilter¶
type: boolean
True if the light cache should be prefiltered to smooth the illumination in it.
prefilter_samples¶
type: int
Number of samples to look for when prefiltering the light cache.
premultiplied¶
type: boolean
true to use premultiplied light cache when possible
retrace_enabled¶
type: boolean
True to enable retrace of the light cache.
retrace_leak_prevention¶
type: float
Enables additional checks to mimize light leaks; 0.0 means no checks
retrace_threshold¶
type: float
Retrace threshold, relative to the light cache sample size.
sample_size¶
type: float
Sample size when calculating the light cache.
show_calc_phase¶
type: boolean
Shows a preview of the scene while the light cache is calculated.
store_direct_light¶
type: boolean
Stores direct lighting with the light cache.
subdivs¶
type: int
Subdivisions for the light cache.
use_for_glossy_rays¶
type: boolean
True if the light cache should be used to estimate GI for glossy rays, instead of the primary GI engine.
world_scale¶
type: boolean
class plugins.SettingsLightLinker¶
ignored_lights¶
type: List
List containing lists of plugins. Every sub list contains a light plugin (always the first element) and some node plugins the light is not illuminating.
ignored_shadow_lights¶
type: List
List containing list of plugins. Every sub list contains a light plugin (always the first element) and some node plugins, which do not cast shadows from this light
include_exclude_light_flags¶
type: List<Integer>
List containing a flag for every light in the ignored_lights list. 0 - the list is an exclude list (default). 1 - the list is an include list. 2 - ignored_lights is ignored and the light illuminates all objects in the scene, useful for animating the light linking.
include_exclude_shadow_flags¶
type: List<Integer>
List containing a flag for every light in the ignored_shadow_lights list. 0 - the list is an exclude list (default). 1 - the list is an include list. 2 - ignored_shadow_lights is ignored and the light casts shadows from all objects in the scene, useful for animating the light linking.

An offset along the geometric surface normal at which to perform shading in order to avoid surface acne.

The base name for the Ptex files
visibility_test_ray_max_length_factor¶
type: float
Maximum length of visibility test ray. It is adjusted by the sample size. If the ray travels at least this length before hitting another object, the sample is considered visible and is shaded, otherwise it’s filled with black when baking to Ptex or entirely ommitted when baking to vrmesh point cloud.
visibility_test_rays¶
type: int
Number of rays shoot to test if sample is actually visible or not. Speeds up shading in the case when parts of the model are occluded. Set to 0 to disable.

type: int
If true then the resolution for each texture will be calculated adaptively, based on the size of the corresponding geometry.

If true then meta data containing the degree of each mesh polygon will be included in the Ptex files.

type: int
If true then meta data containing the vertices of each mesh polygon will be included in the Ptex files.

type: int
If true then meta data containing the positions of all vertices will be included in the Ptex files.

class plugins.SunLight¶
affectDiffuse¶
type: boolean
true if the light produces diffuse lighting and false otherwise
affectSpecular¶
type: boolean
true if the light produces specular hilights and false otherwise
atmos_shadows¶
type: boolean
true if the light casts shadows from atmosperics and false otherwise
blend_angle¶
type: float
The angle (in degrees) (up from the horizon) where the sky starts to blend with the ground albedo. Values close to 0.0 produce a sharper horizon line, while larger values produce a softer horizon line.
bumped_below_surface_check¶
type: boolean
true if the bumped normal should be used to check if the light dir is below the surface

type: float

type: int

type: List<Object>
Render channels the specular result of this light will be written to

type: int
This option affects the way the color in the Filter color parameter affects the color of the sun
diffuseMult¶
type: float
diffuse_contribution¶
type: float
Diffuse contribution for the light
enabled¶
type: boolean
true if the light is casting light (turned on) and false otherwise; it only makes sense to use this parameter if it is animated, or if another object depends on this node but it must not be rendered
filter_color¶
type: Color
Sunlight color. Used to add user control to light color definition
ground_albedo¶
type: Color
Reflective property of the “ground”. Affects sky-dome brightness and color
horiz_illum¶
type: float
Specifies the intensity (in lx) of the illumination on horizontal surfaces coming from the sky
horizon_offset¶
type: float
Horizon offset under the sky-dome. Allows the user to manually lower the horizon line.
intensity_multiplier¶
type: float
invisible¶
type: boolean
When on, this option makes the sun invisible, both to the camera and to reflections
ozone¶
type: float
Affects the color of the sun light (between 0.0 and 1.0). Smaller values make the sunlight more yellow, larger values make it blue
photonSubdivs¶
type: int
photon_radius¶
type: float

type: float
Shadow offset from the surface. Helps to prevent polygonal shadow artifacts on low-poly surfaces.
shadow_color¶
type: Color
The shadow color. Anything but black is not physically accurate.

type: Texture
A color texture that if present will override the shadowColor parameter

true if the light casts shadows and false otherwise

type: float
Controls the visible size of the sun. Affects the appearance of the sun disc as seen by the camera and reflections, as well as the blurriness of the sun shadows

Selects the procedural model used to simulate the TexSky texture

type: Transform

Determines the amount of dust in the air and affects the color of the sun and sky. Smaller values produce a clear/blue sky, larger values yellow and orange

type: Texture

class plugins.TexAColorOp¶
alpha¶
type: OutputTextureFloat
(color_a*mult_a).a
blue¶
type: OutputTextureFloat
(color_a*mult_a).b
color_a¶
type: Texture
The first color
color_b¶
type: Texture
The second color
difference¶
type: OutputTexture
(color_a*mult_a)-(color_b*mult_b)
division¶
type: OutputTexture
(color_a*mult_a)/(color_b*mult_b)
green¶
type: OutputTextureFloat
(color_a*mult_a).g
intensity¶
type: OutputTextureFloat
mult_a*(color_a.r+color_a.g+color_a.b)/3.0
maximum¶
type: OutputTexture
Max(color_a*mult_a , color_b*mult_b)
minimum¶
type: OutputTexture
Min(color_a*mult_a , color_b*mult_b)
mode¶
type: int
Which output should be considered as the output of the main texture (0 - result_a, 1 - result_b, 2 - product, 3 - sum, 4 - difference, 5 - power, 6 - division, 7 - Minimum, 8 - Maximum, 9 - absolute difference), 10 - Lower intensity color, 11 - Greater intensity color
mult_a¶
type: TextureFloat
Multiplier for the first color
mult_b¶
type: TextureFloat
Multiplier for the second color
power¶
type: OutputTexture
(color_a*mult_a)^mult_b
product¶
type: OutputTexture
(color_a*mult_a)*(color_b*mult_b)
red¶
type: OutputTextureFloat
(color_a*mult_a).r
result_a¶
type: OutputTexture
color_a*mult_a
result_alpha¶
type: TextureFloat
The alpha for the result; if not specified, the resulting alpha taken from the first color)
result_b¶
type: OutputTexture
color_b*mult_b
sum¶
type: OutputTexture
(color_a*mult_a)+(color_b*mult_b)
class plugins.TexAnimationCurve¶
input¶
type: TextureFloat
points¶
type: List<Float>
List of control points. Each is represented by six consecutivefloats: 0 - x (time), 1 - y (value), 2 - in-tangent vector x, 3 - in-tangent vector y, 4 - out-tangent vector x, 5 - out-tangent vector y.
post_infinity_type¶
type: int
One of the following: 0 – Constant, 1 – Linear, 2 – Cycle, 3 – Cycle relative, 4 – Oscillate.
pre_infinity_type¶
type: int
One of the following: 0 – Constant, 1 – Linear, 2 – Cycle, 3 – Cycle relative, 4 – Oscillate.
tangent_types¶
type: List<Integer>
Each control point has two tangents. Each of these tangents hasits type. It is specified by an integer from the following table: 0 - Fixed, 1 - Linear, 2 - Flat, 3 - Step, 4 - Step next, 5 - Slow, 6 - Fast, 7 - Smooth, 8 - Clamped, 9 - Plateau, 10 - Auto. For more information on their types, please visit Maya’s documentation website.
weighted¶
type: boolean

class plugins.TexBezierCurve¶
input_float¶
type: TextureFloat
The input texture
num_bezier_points¶
type: int
The number of precisely calculated points from bezier curves: default 256
out_of_range_type¶
type: int
The type of extrapolation for points out of the control range: 0 - end tangnts, 1 - linear, 2 - constant. Used when use_end_tangents is true.
points¶
type: List<Float>
The control points; 6 floats for each point: 2D coords of the point itself, and 2D coords of the left and right tangent.
types¶
type: List<Integer>
The type of the control points: 0 - free, 1 - bezier, 2- bezier smooth
use_end_tangents¶
type: boolean
true to extrapolate beyound the control points
class plugins.TexBezierCurveColor¶
input_color¶
type: Texture
The input color texture.
num_bezier_points_b¶
type: int
The number of precisely calculated points from bezier curves: default 256. If points_b is not set, num_bezier_points_r will be used instead
num_bezier_points_g¶
type: int
The number of precisely calculated points from bezier curves: default 256. If points_g is not set, num_bezier_points_r will be used instead
num_bezier_points_r¶
type: int
The number of precisely calculated points from bezier curves: default 256.
out_of_range_type_b¶
type: int
The type of extrapolation for points out of the control range: 0 - end tangnts, 1 - linear, 2 - constant. Used when use_end_tangents is true. If points_b is empty, out_of_range_type_r will be used instead
out_of_range_type_g¶
type: int
The type of extrapolation for points out of the control range: 0 - end tangnts, 1 - linear, 2 - constant. Used when use_end_tangents is true. If points_g is empty, out_of_range_type_r will be used instead
out_of_range_type_r¶
type: int
The type of extrapolation for points out of the control range: 0 - end tangnts, 1 - linear, 2 - constant. Used when use_end_tangents is true.
points_b¶
type: List<Float>
The control points for B channel. If this is empty, points_r will be used instead; 6 floats for each point: 2D coords of the point itself, and 2D coords of the left and right tangent.
points_g¶
type: List<Float>
The control points for G channel. If this is empty, points_r will be used instead; 6 floats for each point: 2D coords of the point itself, and 2D coords of the left and right tangent.
points_r¶
type: List<Float>
The control points for R channel. If there are no G or B control points, this control points will be used instead; 6 floats for each point: 2D coords of the point itself, and 2D coords of the left and right tangent.
types_b¶
type: List<Integer>
The type of the control points: 0 - free, 1 - bezier, 2- bezier smooth. If points_b is empty, types_r will be used
types_g¶
type: List<Integer>
The type of the control points: 0 - free, 1 - bezier, 2- bezier smooth. If points_g is empty, types_r will be used
types_r¶
type: List<Integer>
The type of the control points: 0 - free, 1 - bezier, 2- bezier smooth.
use_end_tangents_b¶
type: boolean
true to extrapolate beyound the control points. If points_b is empty, use_end_tangents_r will be used instead
use_end_tangents_g¶
type: boolean
true to extrapolate beyound the control points. If points_g is empty, use_end_tangents_r will be used instead
use_end_tangents_r¶
type: boolean
true to extrapolate beyound the control points.

class plugins.TexDistance¶

An additional offset for the texture color
compatibility_with¶
type: int
This is used to differentiate between textures exported from different applications. The value means : 0 - 3ds Max (this is also the default), 1 - Maya, ...
distance¶
type: TextureFloat
Specifies a radius outside of which all points will be given the far color.
far_tex¶
type: Texture
The color returned by the texture for points that are at a distance greater than the radius parameter from the specified objects.
inside_separate¶
type: boolean
When this option is enabled, the near color value will be overridden by the inside color value for points that are inside the specified geometry.
inside_solid¶
type: boolean
When this option is enabled, all the points inside the specified geometry are given the inside color value and no blending is performed.
inside_tex¶
type: Texture
The color returned by the texture for points that are right inside the specified object(s). For points that are inside the objects, but not exactly next to them the color will be determined by blending between the inside color and the far color and the radius will serve as a falloff radius.
invert¶
type: boolean
If true, the resulting texture color will be inverted
invert_alpha¶
type: boolean
If true and invert is on, the resulting texture alpha will be inverted too. If false, just the color will be inverted
near_tex¶
type: Texture
The color returned by the texture for points that are right at the edges of the specified object(s).For points that are outside or inside the objects, but not exactly next to the them, the color will be determined by blending between the near color and the far color and the radius will serve as a falloff radius.
nouvw_color¶
type: Texture
The color when there are no valid uvw coordinates
objects¶
type: List<Object>
List of nodes to measure distance to.

type: OutputTextureFloat
The resulting alpha
out_intensity¶
type: OutputTextureFloat
The resulting intensity
out_transparency¶
type: OutputTexture
The resulting transparency
outside_separate¶
type: boolean
When this option is enabled, the near color value will be overridden by the outside color value for points that are outside the specified geometry.
outside_solid¶
type: boolean
When this option is enabled, all the points outside the specified geometry are given the outside color value and no blending is performed.
outside_tex¶
type: Texture
The color returned by the texture for points that are right outside the specified object(s). For points that are outside the objects, but not exactly next to them, the color will be determined by blending between the outside color and the far color and the radius will serve as a falloff radius.

class plugins.TexDistanceToObject¶
object¶
type: Object
This parameter references an object that implements the EXT_WORLD_MATRIX interface. Given such an object, the texture result is the distance between that object and the point currently being sampled. Distance is measured in world units. In case of error, texture yields zero.
